note as CycleLegend
  <b>Recursive dependencies detected and resolved</b>
  The following edges were removed to enable ordering:
  Patient → PatientQueue
  Patient → UrgencyLevel
  Mutually recursive groups:
  [Patient, PatientQueue, UrgencyLevel]
end note

note as RelationshipCorrections
  <b>Relationship cardinalities corrected by LLM review</b>
  DashboardAccessOperation "1" --> "some" Interface → DashboardAccessOperation "1" --> "*" Interface
    Reason: The cardinality 'some' is not standard; replaced with '*' to indicate multiple interfaces.
  DashboardAccessOperation "1" --> "some" Resource → DashboardAccessOperation "1" --> "*" Resource
    Reason: The cardinality 'some' is not standard; replaced with '*' to indicate multiple resources.
  Patient "1" --> "1" UrgencyLevel → Patient "*" --> "1" UrgencyLevel
    Reason: Multiple patients can have the same urgency level, so cardinality should be many-to-one.
  Patient *-- PatientRecord → Patient "1" --> "1" PatientRecord
    Reason: Composition is not appropriate; each patient has exactly one record, so use one-to-one directed association.
  Patient --> PatientQueue → PatientQueue "1" --> "*" Patient
    Reason: Direction reversed: queue contains many patients, so queue should reference patient with one-to-many cardinality.
  PatientQueue *-- "0..*" Patient → PatientQueue --* "0..*" Patient
    Reason: Composition arrow should have diamond on the whole side (queue), indicating one queue contains many patients.
  Queue "1" *--> "*" Patient → Queue --* "*" Patient
    Reason: Composition arrow should have diamond on the whole side (queue), indicating one queue contains many patients.
  Resource "1" --> "1" Actor → Resource "1" --> "*" Actor
    Reason: A resource can be used by multiple actors, so cardinality should be one-to-many.
  TriageNurse "1" --> "1" PatientRecord → TriageNurse "1" --> "*" PatientRecord
    Reason: A triage nurse can create multiple patient records, so cardinality should be one-to-many.
end note

note as ArchitectureCorrections
  <b>Architecture mistakes corrected automatically</b>
  [duplicate_concept] There are two queue classes: 'Queue' and 'PatientQueue'. The tasks consistently refer to 'PatientQueue' as the class owning the queue logic. The 'Queue' class is redundant and likely a leftover from an earlier design.
    Fix applied: remove_class
  [missing_relationship] TriageNurse and Physician are both types of medical staff, but there is no inheritance relationship defined. According to the domain, they should be subclasses of MedicalStaff to reflect shared behavior and properties.
    Fix applied: add_relation
  [missing_relationship] Similarly, Physician should be a subclass of MedicalStaff.
    Fix applied: add_relation
  [other_correction] PatientQueue has three conflicting associations with Patient (a directed association with multiplicity, another directed association without multiplicity, and a composition). This is inconsistent and should be unified to a single composition indicating that PatientQueue owns Patients.
    Fix applied: remove_relation
  [other_correction] Remove the second conflicting directed association between PatientQueue and Patient.
    Fix applied: remove_relation
  [other_correction] Keep only the composition arrow from PatientQueue to Patient, which correctly models ownership.
    Fix applied: add_relation
  [wrong_class_type] Patient has two separate associations to UrgencyLevel (one with multiplicity and one without). The redundant one should be removed.
    Fix applied: remove_relation
end note

package "Task #3\nQueue Sorting by Urgency\nand Arrival Time" {
  class PatientQueue <<main>> <<level1>>
  class Queue
}

package "Task #1\nPatient Registration\nwith Symptoms" {
  class Patient <<main>> <<level2>>
  class SymptomResource
}

package "Task #2\nUrgency Level Assignment" {
  enum UrgencyLevel <<main>> <<level0>>
  class MedicalStaff
  class PatientCareTeam
  class PatientRecord
  class TriageNurse
}

package "Task #5\nPatient Dequeue for\nPhysician" {
  note as TaskSummary5
    No new domain model classes
    Uses: Patient, PatientQueue
  end note
}

package "Task #4\nDynamic Requeuing on New\nPatient or Re-triage" {
  note as TaskSummary4
    No new domain model classes
    Uses: Patient, PatientQueue, UrgencyLevel
  end note
}

package "Task #6\nLive Dashboard with\nUrgency and Wait Time" {
  note as TaskSummary6
    No new domain model classes
    Uses: Patient, UrgencyLevel, PatientQueue
  end note
}

